              <h2>Geometric Formulas for Circle Properties</h2>
              <p>The entire geometry of a circle can be calculated if the radius ($r$) is known. The relationships are defined by the constant $\pi \approx 3.14159$ .</p>

              <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse my-4">
                <thead>
                  <tr class="bg-blue-100">
                    <th class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2 font-semibold">Property</th>
                    <th class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2 font-semibold">Formula (using $r$)</th>
                    <th class="border border-blue-300 px-4 py-2 font-semibold">Inverse Formula (to find $r$)</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-300 px-4 py-2">Diameter ($d$)</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-300 px-4 py-2">$d = 2r$</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-300 px-4 py-2">$r = d/2$</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-300 px-4 py-2">Circumference ($C$)</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-300 px-4 py-2">$C = 2\pi r$</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-300 px-4 py-2">$$r = \frac{C}{2\pi}$$</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-300 px-4 py-2">Area ($A$)</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-300 px-4 py-2">$A = \pi r^2$</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-300 px-4 py-2">$$r = \sqrt{\frac{A}{\pi}}$$</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>

              <h2>Circle Equations (Analytic Geometry)</h2>
              <p>In a coordinate plane, the location and size of a circle are described by its equation. The circle is defined as the set of all points $(x, y)$ that are equidistant (distance $r$) from a fixed center point $(h, k)$.</p>
              
              <h3>Standard Form (Center-Radius Form)</h3>
              <p>This is the simplest form, directly showing the center $(h, k)$ and the radius $r$:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-center text-lg font-medium">
                $$(x - h)^2 + (y - k)^2 = r^2$$
              </div>
              
              <h3>General Form</h3>
              <p>The general form is found by expanding the standard form:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-center text-lg font-medium">
                $$x^2 + y^2 + Dx + Ey + F = 0$$
              </div>
              <p>Where the center coordinates are related by $h = -D/2$ and $k = -E/2$.</p>

              <h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>
              <div class="space-y-4">
                <div>
                  <h3 class="font-semibold cursor-pointer" data-faq-toggle>What is the formula for the Area of a Circle?</h3>
                  <div class="faq-content hidden mt-2 pl-4">
                    <p>The area ($A$) of a circle is calculated by multiplying pi ($\pi \approx 3.14159$) by the square of the radius ($r$): $A = \pi r^2$.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <h3 class="font-semibold cursor-pointer" data-faq-toggle>What is the formula for the Circumference of a Circle?</h3>
                  <div class="faq-content hidden mt-2 pl-4">
                    <p>The circumference ($C$), which is the distance around the circle, is calculated as pi ($\pi$) times the diameter ($d$), or two times pi times the radius ($r$): $C = \pi d = 2\pi r$.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <h3 class="font-semibold cursor-pointer" data-faq-toggle>What is the standard form equation of a circle?</h3>
                  <div class="faq-content hidden mt-2 pl-4">
                    <p>The standard form equation of a circle with center $(h, k)$ and radius $r$ is: $(x - h)^2 + (y - k)^2 = r^2$.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <h3 class="font-semibold cursor-pointer" data-faq-toggle>What is the relationship between the circle and the ellipse?</h3>
                  <div class="faq-content hidden mt-2 pl-4">
                    <p>A circle is a special case of an ellipse where the two semi-axes are equal ($a = b = r$) and the eccentricity ($e$) is zero. Geometrically, it is the only conic section with $A=C$ in the general form $A x^2 + C y^2 + D x + E y + F = 0$.</p>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>

